The present Lady Ashburton is far past yawning! has indeed—(so Lord A wrote to his Brother Frederick Baring, who had not had a scrape of a pen from him since the marriage,)—has indeed “passed the critical point at which the dear Girl had miscarried hitherto.” Twice she had miscarried, Lord A told my Husband, “with the simple ingenuousness of a young Boy” (these were Mr C’s words). also Mr C said, that Lord A, to do him justice, seemed “extremely anxious that the thing should get itself born this time;
      Mary Florence Baring was born 26 June 1860.
       much more out of anxiety about his wife’s health, than from any selfish notions about an heir!” In fact Lord A and Mr C talking together on this subject, with their mutual “simple ingenuousness” must be something grand to hear!

Do you know the Auckland Eden-House people?Emily Eden (1797–1869; 
  ODNB
), novelist and society hostess, lived at Eden Lodge, Upper Gore, Kensington; sister of George Eden (1784–1849), 2d Baron Auckland, statesman, governor-general of India (1835–42), who had been one of the Ashburton circle and had d. of a sudden apoplexy at The Grange on 1 Jan. 1849; Emily’s niece Lena Eden (b. 1826), da. of Robert John Eden (1799–1870; 
  ODNB
), bishop of Bath and Wells and 3d Baron Auckland, also lived at Eden Lodge. Some Letters have turned up there;The Athenaeum reported, 7 April, “A MORNING AT EDEN LODGE / A few days ago we passed a very pleasant morning in the library at Eden Lodge. [It] is a charming place,—old books, old trees, a sunny lawn. … But the interest of the moment centres, not in trees and books, but in certain chests of old letters and papers about the great and illustrious dead. In these records one lives again, in the society … of some of the most renowned men and women of the last century. … / We begin our selections with a note from Hugh Elliott, our resident Minister at the Court of Frederick the Great. It will interest Mr. Carlyle.” The letter, dated “Berlin, December 18, 1777,” is from Hugh Elliot (1752–1830; 
  ODNB
), diplomat, minister in Berlin 1777–82, and addressed to his brother-in-law William Eden (1744–1814; 
  ODNB
), 1st Baron Auckland, politician and penal reformer.—a small portion of whh may (or perhaps not) concern Fritz and me a little.A selection of the letters was pbd. in The Journal and Correspondence of William, Lord Auckland, ed. Robert John Eden, 4 vols. (1861–62). There is very little mention of Frederick, and TC does not cite the book but does quote another letter from Elliot to William Eden; Works 19:179. I used to know a Miss Eden,—alas, alas! But I think she too is gone from us.Presumably Emily’s sister, Fanny (ca. 1797–1849). There were six other sisters, all married.—— Offer Lord Sandwich my regards if he will have them. And adieu for Today.— 
  Yours ever

      T. Carlyle
      Mary Langridge (not further identified) wrote to TC, 18 April: “May I beg for the enclosed your kind perusal, and may I hope that it will commend itself to your sympathy and support. It may be an odd appeal to make to you, who scare orthodox folk from venturing near your charmed circle, but I am greatly mistaken if Thomas Carlyle will not yield an approving smile and a helping hand to the man, who with an honest and brave heart is endeavouring to work out his highest idea of life—that of spending and being spent, for what he conceives to be the good of his fellow men. My hand quite trembles from a consciousness of my temerity in addressing so great a man, but the greatest are also the gentlest, and I can not forget that from your pen has streamed into my room, and my head, hands, mind and heart—thoughts and feelings which have strengthened … them in many an hour of trial.” The enclosure is unidentified.

The Duke of Manchester is here, DuchessWilliam Drogo Montagu, 7th duke of Manchester, and Luise Friederike Auguste, duchess. coming today,—and Hepworth 
DixonWilliam Hepworth Dixon (1821–79; 
  ODNB
), journalist and writer; editor of the Athenaeum, 1853–69. is expected for certain! Gott im Himmel.— The Evening wd really have been pleasant,—the Owner of Oliver Cromwell’s House,George Rust (ca. 1795–1876), justice of the peace. Cromwell’s house, originally an Augustinian friary, located at the N end of Huntingdon, was acquired by Sir Henry Cromwell in 1568. He gave it to his younger son, Robert (d. 1617), father of Oliver Cromwell, who was born there in 1599. Oliver Cromwell sold the house in 1631. George Rust’s father, James Rust (ca. 1747–1827), bought it in 1810. an excellt simple old gentn, & another Huntingdon figure of like quality,Unidentified. were here for my sake;—and I like Lord Sandwich really well, and find an intelligt rugged son of Nature in him, who seems to like me too in spite of his astonisht: but—but—the truth is, they kept me talking, in a tabagie [smoking room] they have till one in the morning (my own sumphhood again); and I am “like an electrified Cat”;—and see nothing for it, with Hepworth ahead, but that I must fly home tomorrow after noon. It will be abt 4½ or 4 p.m. I guess; if I don’t come then, think I have slept a little better tonight; and do not look for me till Monday abt the same hour. Oh my Dearest, if I had not thee, what wd become of me! 
  God keep thee, and bless thee.
— T. Carlyle

