I had your second and your third Note,John A. Carlyle wrote from Aboukir Villa, Bridge of Allan, 8 Aug.: “I fear my letter of last night was very confused indeed, representing the state in which I arrived from Inverness; so I will send you a few words this night also to make amends.” both of which were very welcome to me; write to me again whenever you have a few minutes of leisure; news of you, and of the news you may hear from the South whence I yet hear nothing, are always desirable. Dr Hunter2. Dr. Jacob Hunter (ca. 1810–89; see 23:114 TC to JAC, 19 Sept. 1848
), an old friend of John’s, was “journeying in the Highlands” but intended returning 9 Aug. John wrote: “So I shall probably see him too. But I rather enjoy the utter solitude in the mean time, & care little whether he comes or not.” I hope has by this time joined you, whh will yield society in your new villa; nothing else is wanting to render it pleasant. I
recollect that Country very well: it was the scene of the first tour I ever made,-to the Trosachs, along with good Edward Irving and others, many long years ago!The Trossachs is a picturesque wooded area of hills, crags, and gorges in SW Perthshire, 10 mi. W of Bridge of Allan. For TC’s walking tour with Edward Irving, Mr. Piers (Irving’s housemate), and James Brown (1786–1830), Aug. 1817, see Carlyle, Reminiscences 230–36. The water of Teith was extremely blue, vocal and beautiful; Stirling too pleased me much; infinitely more my first glimpse of the Highlands and the Lochs and Bens: indeed all was new to me, and joyously impressive, at that time. I think you shd try to return by Loch Katrine;The river Teith flows from Loch Venacher, W of Callander (16 mi. NW of Stirling), into the river Forth near Stirling. Loch Katrine, about 8 mi. in length, lies 8½ mi. W of Callander. I have never since seen so pretty a Lake and “Split-Grounds” (Trosachs):“Trossachs” means “bristled country” or rough ground in Gaelic. but I suppose it is infested by crowds at present. We went across from it to Loch Lomond; crossed to Tarbet, west side of the Loch, where was an excellt country inn:— Steamers will now take you, at all times of the day (I suppose), to GlasgowTarbet, on the W side of Loch Lomond, 30 mi. N of Glasgow; Loch Lomond, the largest loch in Scotland, 22 mi. long and 5 mi. broad at its widest part, drains at its S end into the river Leven which flows through the Vale of Leven to the Clyde. The Caledonian and Dumbartonshire Railway from Balloch (on the loch) to Bowling (on the Clyde) opened 1850, with steamer connections at both ends (on the loch and to Glasgow). Loch Lomond was described by the Rev. John Wilson in 1882: “The scenery of its upper parts is predominantly sublime; of its lower parts, predominantly ornate; of its central parts, a rich intermixture of beauty, brilliance, and grandeur” (The Gazetteer of Scotland [Edinburgh, 1882] 310). whence there is rail either to Dumfrs or Ecclefechan.
